264 1452 365 ( Status:         resolved) 365 SB
264 1502 219 ( Description:) 219 SB
264 1552 326 (         24.1.1 p24-2:) 326 SB
264 1602 991 ( What are the semantics of input iterators in the following:) 991 SB
264 1652 311 (    input_iterator i;) 311 SB
264 1702 515 (    cout << *i;       // Object "a") 515 SB
264 1752 862 (    cout << *i;       // Continues to return object "a"?) 862 SB
264 1802 1213 (     /* This seems to be implied by requirement a == b implies *a == *b.) 1213 SB
264 1852 674 (        Therefore *a == *a should be true.) 674 SB
264 1902 1064 (        This implies the input object is 'saved' in some fashion. */) 1064 SB
264 2002 368 (    input_iterator j = i;) 368 SB
264 2052 514 (    cout << *j;       // Object "a") 514 SB
1689 302 116 (    ++i;) 116 SB
1689 352 516 (    cout << *i;       // Object "b") 516 SB
1689 402 844 (    cout << *j;       // Object "a", "b", or undefined?) 844 SB
1689 452 1023 (     /* Returning "b" implies that all input iterators remain in) 1023 SB
1689 502 1035 (        lockstep and all point to the same item.  This is not how) 1035 SB
1689 552 432 (        other iterators work.) 432 SB
1689 652 1032 (        Undefined implies that changing a different iterator can) 1032 SB
1689 702 1009 (        affect the value of this iterator, even though no change) 1009 SB
1689 752 597 (        has been made to this iterator.) 597 SB
1689 852 1057 (        Returning "a" is how other iterators work.  It implies that) 1057 SB
1689 902 1029 (        the 'saved' object is not destroyed when an input occurs.) 1029 SB
1689 952 1063 (        Bill Plauger states that several STL algorithms depend on) 1063 SB
1689 1002 339 (        this behaviour.) 339 SB
1689 1052 88 (     */) 88 SB
1689 1152 944 (    ++j;              // What is the effect on j after i has been) 944 SB
1689 1202 1001 (                      // incremented; object "b", "c", or undefined?) 1001 SB
1689 1302 1130 ( Nathan Myers proposes a change to semantics of copying in 3943:) 1130 SB
1689 1352 1124 (    Copying an input iterator should invalidate the previous version) 1124 SB
1689 1402 1018 (    of the iterator.  This ensures that there is only one current) 1018 SB
1689 1452 953 (    version of the iterator usable for ++.  It would prevent) 953 SB
1689 1502 1068 (    dereferencing of the copied version of the iterator. [See 3943) 1068 SB
1689 1552 508 (    for a complete description].) 508 SB
1689 1652 894 ( Andy Koenig proposes a simplified scheme in 4114:) 894 SB
1689 1702 1163 (    Copying an input iterator does not invalidate the previous version.) 1163 SB
1689 1752 1179 (    Both may be dereferenced until one is incremented.  It is undefined) 1179 SB
1689 1802 990 (    to dereference any copy other than the one incremented.) 990 SB
1689 1902 163 (Summary) 163 SB
1689 1952 1057 ( Various other messages discuss the relative merits of different) 1057 SB
1689 2002 795 ( semantics.  There are three proposed methods.) 795 SB
